	3.	Jackson Serialization and Deserialization Behavior
	•	If characterSetType is missing from the request, the default behavior is to set it to null.
	•	Spring will not convert a missing field into an empty object automatically unless you initialize it explicitly.

🔹 Solution: Differentiate Search and Response Models

Instead of using the same AddressDetailsDTO in both search and response, we can separate concerns.

✅ Fix 1: Use a Separate AddressSearchDetailsDTO
	•	Keep AddressDetailsDTO for response.
	•	Create a new DTO for search, allowing optional fields.

Updated AddressSearchDetailsDTO

import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonInclude;
import lombok.Data;

@Data
@JsonInclude(JsonInclude.Include.NON_NULL) // Exclude null values from JSON response
public class AddressSearchDetailsDTO {
    private CharacterSetType characterSetType;
    private String postalCode;
    private String country;
    private String prefecture;
    private String city;
    private String town;
    private String lane;
}

	•	This allows characterSetType to be missing in search without causing null issues.
	•	Using @JsonInclude(JsonInclude.Include.NON_NULL) ensures that missing fields are ignored instead of explicitly setting them to null.

